&lt;p class=MsoNormal align=center style='text-align:center'>&lt;b>&lt;span
style='font-size:12.0pt'>&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span>&lt;/b>&lt;/p>
&lt;p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>&lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt'>            Many
of the examples below raise issues that are not in themselves very important. We
offer them, however, as (1) “exercises” in hermeneutical creativity on matters
where frankly it does not hurt to be wrong. Besides, it is not healthy to get
in the habit of “dodging” critical issues because they impact (2) evaluating
biblical accuracy. Though the points themselves are often not significant,
their existence in a religious text does raise a point that &lt;u>is&lt;/u>
significant—whether people can trust the biblical accounts. Distrusting them
for unnecessary reasons should be avoided, and we cannot legitimately trust
them without correct exegetical work as a means of properly avoiding
unnecessary criticism of scripture.&lt;/span>&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>BRAIN TEASERS</title><link>https://christir.org/essays/interpretation/brain-teasers/brain-teasers/</link><pubDate>Thu, 02 Apr 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://christir.org/essays/interpretation/brain-teasers/brain-teasers/</guid><description>&lt;style>
